{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529896"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:59:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:59:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14473"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14473"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.45,0.02,0.07,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7168"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55672"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7168"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14473"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41215"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1022"},{"type":"tags","id":"1096"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"2118"},{"type":"tags","id":"4353"},{"type":"tags","id":"4450"},{"type":"tags","id":"4452"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17577"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17591"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40113"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55672"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman is transferred to the labour ward at 26 weeks gestation with a four-hour history of regular painful contractions. She has no significant medical history and this is her first pregnancy. She does not take any regular medications. She ruptured her membranes 2 days earlier and has been on the maternity ward. She has already had neonatal steroids, nifedipine and oral antibiotics. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. On abdominal examination, the uterus is tender and contracting every three minutes. Vaginal examination reveals 4 cm cervical dilatation, fully effaced, -1 station. A complete breech presentation is confirmed on ultrasound. Investigations reveal a white cell count of 18 x 10^9/L (4-11) and C-reactive protein of 80 mg/L (\u0026lt;5).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate type of caesarean section for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["J-shaped caesarean section","Lower segment caesarean section","Extraperitoneal caesarean section","Low vertical caesarean section","Classical caesarean section"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with preterm labour at 26 weeks gestation, complicated by chorioamnionitis and breech presentation. Given these factors, an emergency caesarean section is indicated. The most appropriate type in this scenario is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eclassical caesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eclassical caesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E involves a vertical incision in the upper segment of the uterus. It is preferred in this case for several reasons: 1) At 26 weeks, the lower uterine segment is often not well-formed, making a lower segment approach difficult. 2) The vertical incision provides better access for delivering a preterm breech baby. 3) It allows for a faster delivery, which is crucial given the presence of chorioamnionitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elower segment caesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common type performed at term. However, at 26 weeks, the lower segment is often not adequately developed, making this approach less suitable and potentially more difficult.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elow vertical caesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used for preterm deliveries but is less commonly performed than either classical or lower segment approaches. It doesn\u0027t offer significant advantages over a classical incision in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EJ-shaped caesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E combines a transverse lower segment incision with a vertical extension. While it can be used for some preterm deliveries, it\u0027s not typically the first choice for a very preterm breech presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eextraperitoneal caesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely performed in modern obstetrics. It was historically used to reduce the risk of peritoneal contamination in cases of infection, but modern surgical and antibiotic practices have largely eliminated the need for this approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while a classical caesarean section provides the best access for this preterm breech delivery, it does carry increased risks for future pregnancies, including uterine rupture and the need for repeat caesarean deliveries. The patient should be counselled about these long-term implications when possible. Additionally, broad-spectrum antibiotics should be administered to treat the chorioamnionitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Classical caesarean section is indicated for preterm breech deliveries, especially when there is inadequate time for a lower segment to form.","Chorioamnionitis increases the risk of postpartum complications and requires prompt delivery and antibiotic treatment.","Preterm labour management involves careful consideration of maternal and fetal risks, including the potential need for emergency delivery."],"references":[]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41215"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14473"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41215"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-17T14:23:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T14:24:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7168"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55672"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null